# Escape Hatch Registry

> Copy this file to your project root as `escapes.md`. Every intentional deviation
> from the plugin's axioms lives here, with a justification and an expiry date.
> `bin/css-strict.sh` and `bin/js-budget.sh` read this file directly: a registered,
> **unexpired** escape suppresses the matching violation and the gate stays green;
> an **expired** escape, or a violation with **no** escape, fails the gate.

## How this works

The plugin's six axioms (`skills/css-layout-engine/references/axioms.md`) are
enforced by `bin/css-strict.sh` (ELA_001–006) and `bin/js-budget.sh` (ELA_005).
When a violation is intentional — a third-party widget you can't strip, a legacy
route awaiting migration, an editorial page that breaks the system on purpose —
you register it in the table below. The build stays green; the debt stays visible.

The gates parse the **Active escapes** table. The match key is **(Target, Axiom, Lines)**:

- **Target** is a shell glob matched against the file path the gate reports. `*`
  matches any characters **including `/`**, so `demos/*` covers everything under
  `demos/`, and `*/embed.css` matches `embed.css` anywhere. For `js-budget.sh`,
  the target is matched against the dist-relative path of the over-budget `.js`
  file; the reserved target `page-total` suppresses a page-total overage.
- **Axiom** is the exact `ELA_###` id the gate emits (`ELA_001`…`ELA_006`).
- **Lines** scopes the escape to specific line numbers: `-` (or empty) covers
  **every** line of the matching file; `9`, `9,10`, or `9-11` covers only those
  lines, so an accidental same-axiom violation elsewhere in the file still fails.
  Prefer the narrowest scope. `js-budget.sh` has no line concept, so its routes
  only match file-level (`-`) escapes.
- **Expires** is an ISO date (`YYYY-MM-DD`), inclusive — the escape is expired
  once today is past it. There is no "never": unbounded debt is forbidden. For a
  genuinely long-lived third-party constraint, use a far-future review date
  (e.g. `2099-12-31`) so the entry stays visible and re-reviewable.

A row is recognised only when its Axiom column is an `ELA_###` id and its Expires
column is an ISO date, so the header/separator rows and any prose are ignored.
Put **one (Target, Axiom) entry per row** — if one file needs two axioms suppressed,
write two rows. For reproducible CI, the gate's notion of "today" can be pinned
with the `ESCAPES_TODAY=YYYY-MM-DD` environment variable.

## Field reference

| Column | Required | Used by gate | Description |
|--------|----------|--------------|-------------|
| **ESC ID** | Yes | message only | One of the canonical categories below, or a project-specific `ESC_<CATEGORY>`. Shown in the "suppressed by …" message. |
| **Target (glob)** | Yes | **match key** | File path / glob the violation occurs in (backticks optional). |
| **Axiom** | Yes | **match key** | The exact `ELA_###` being suppressed for this target. |
| **Lines** | Yes | **match key** | `-` for the whole file, or `9` / `9,10` / `9-11` to scope to line numbers. |
| **Expires** | Yes | **expiry check** | ISO date; inclusive. Expired entries fail the gate. |
| **Owner** | Yes | message only | @handle accountable for the exception. |
| **Justification** | Yes | message only | One sentence: what the canonical alternative looked like and why it was rejected. |

Canonical `ESC_*` categories (immutable — never renamed or removed):
`ESC_EDITORIAL`, `ESC_EMBED`, `ESC_DATAVIZ`, `ESC_LEGACY`, `ESC_JS_EAGER`,
`ESC_JS_EXCESS`. Add project-specific `ESC_<CATEGORY>` ids as needed.

## Review cadence

- Quarterly review of every entry. If still justified, extend `Expires` with a fresh note.
- If the justification no longer holds, remove the row and fix the underlying violation.
- If the violation was registered under false pretenses, remove the row and open a ticket.

